INSERT INTO `blog` VALUES (1,'How class Loaders work in java ?',' Classloader in java is a class which is used to load class files in JVM. The java files are first compiled by javac into class files. When run( java <classname> )command is given or at the runtime class files are loaded, class loaders load the class into the jvm memory.When a classloading request is recieved by the classloader subsystem, Application Classloader recieves the request and delegates the request to Extention Classloader which in turn delegates the request to Bootstrap Classloader.','\n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          \n          <p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\">What is a classloader&nbsp;</span></b><b><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\">?</span></b><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">A class loader is a class which loads the java class into JVM memory</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\">How does a Classloader works&nbsp;</span></b><b><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\">?</span></b><b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 13.5pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">To understand how a Classloader works, first you should understand the architecture of&nbsp;<b>JVM .</b>A JVM has following major components.</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></p><ol start=\"1\" type=\"1\" style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">Classloader subsystem.</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">Memory Area</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">Runtime Engine</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;\">Native Interface</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\"><o:p></o:p></span></li></ol><p style=\"margin: 0em 0.2em 1em; font-family: Verdana, Geneva, Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 24px; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); word-wrap: break-word; text-align: justify; font-size: 15px !important;\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; text-align: center;\"><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;, serif; font-size: 12pt;\">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<img src=\"https://coderszone.in/service/upfile/get/1466840727682/png\" style=\"width: 747px;\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\">&nbsp;<b><font face=\"Tahoma\">1) Classloader Subsystem</font></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\">&nbsp; Classloader subsystems task is devided into 3 steps .</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal; text-align: center;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=\"https://coderszone.in/service/upfile/get/1467119405965/png\" style=\"width: 596px;\"></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><font face=\"Arial Black\">A)</font><b><font face=\"Arial Black\">&nbsp;Loading</font></b></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"></p><p><font face=\"Helvetica\">Loading means loading the classfiles into method area (Jvm Memory). The loading is done by class loaders. Classloaders are of three types .<br></font>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1) Bootstrap Classloader<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;2) Extention Classloader<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3) Application Classloader<br><font face=\"Verdana\">The classes are load by these three classloaders using&nbsp;<font color=\"#085294\"><b>delegation hierarchy</b></font>&nbsp;principle. Which ensures&nbsp;delegation, visibility and uniqueness.<br><br><b>What is Delegation Heirarchy principle?<br></b><br>When a classloading request is recieved by the classloader subsystem, Application Classloader recieves the request and delegates the request to Extention Classloader which in turn delegates the request to Bootstrap Classloader.<br>So Eventualy bootstrap classloader is the first Classloader which try first to load the class from&nbsp;JRE/lib/rt.jar. If it fails to find that class in&nbsp;</font><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; line-height: 26.6px;\">JRE/lib/rt.jar it delegates back to Extention classloader to load the class. Now extention classloader try to load the class from&nbsp;</span><font face=\"Verdana\">JRE/lib/ext</font><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.9;\">&nbsp;.If it finds the class in ext it loads the .class file byte code into the Method Area of JVM memory. If it still doesnot find the class it will be delegated back to the Application Classloader to load this Class. So Application Classloader try to find the class in the classpath (</span><font face=\"Verdana\">CLASSPATH environment variable, -classpath or -cp). if it finds the .class file in the classpath it loads the bytecode of .class file into the method Area</font><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.9;\">&nbsp;otherwise it throws&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: Consolas, Menlo, Monaco, &quot;Lucida Console&quot;, &quot;Liberation Mono&quot;, &quot;DejaVu Sans Mono&quot;, &quot;Bitstream Vera Sans Mono&quot;, &quot;Courier New&quot;, monospace, sans-serif; color: rgb(36, 39, 41); font-size: 13px; line-height: 16.9px; white-space: pre-wrap; background-color: rgb(239, 240, 241);\">java.lang.ClassNotFoundException</span><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.9;\">&nbsp; . &nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p><p style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;<img src=\"https://coderszone.in/service/upfile/get/1467119535249/png\" style=\"width: 836px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 1.9;\"><br></span></p><ol style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><li><font face=\"Verdana\">Request for classloading is recieved to Application Classloader. It delegates the task to extention Classloader.</font></li><li><font face=\"Verdana\">Extention classloader recieves the request and delegates it to the bootstrap classloader (Primordial classloader).</font></li><li><font face=\"Verdana\">Bootstrap classloader looks into the rt.jar for the class and loads the class if found.&nbsp;</font></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 25.6px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp;<span style=\"line-height: 25.6px;\">Otherwise..it&nbsp;</span>delegates back to extention classloader to load the class.</font></span></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 25.6px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">Extention classloader tries to load the class from ext libraries. if it finds the .class file, it loads the class.</font></span></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 25.6px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">Otherwise ..it delegates the task back to the calling Classloader(Application Classloader) .</font></span></li><li><span style=\"line-height: 25.6px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">Application classloader tries to load the class from classpaths. if it finds the .class file, it loads the class.</font></span></li><li><font face=\"Verdana\">otherwise&nbsp;<font color=\"#085294\">ClassNotFoundException&nbsp;</font>is thrown.</font></li></ol><p class=\"MsoNormal\" style=\"line-height: normal;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; line-height: 26.6px;\">This ensures the security as core classes can only be loaded by using bootstrap classloader.</span></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><span style=\"font-family: Verdana; font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 26.6px;\">Till now we have seen the principles of delegation heirarchy and visibility and uniqueness. however DO NOTE THAT this can be broken using custom Classloaders.<br>However The class loading process is done by calling following&nbsp;<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/ClassLoader.html#loadClass(java.lang.String,%20boolean)\">loadclass()</a>&nbsp;function from&nbsp;</span><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/ClassLoader.html\">Classloader</a>&nbsp;.</p><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">public abstract class ClassLoader {</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;...</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;...<br></font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font face=\"Verdana\">public Class&lt;?&gt; loadClass(String name) throws ClassNotFoundException {<br></font><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font face=\"Verdana\">return loadClass(name, false);<br></font><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp; &nbsp; </font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font face=\"Verdana\">}<br></font>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;...<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;...<br>}</pre><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">So letus see and analyze the code of loadClass in specific.</font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><br></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 1038px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\"><br></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\"></font></p><p style=\"margin-bottom: 0px;\"><font face=\"Verdana\" style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1; text-transform: uppercase;\">&nbsp;&nbsp;</font><span style=\"font-size: 1rem; line-height: 1; text-transform: uppercase;\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p></p><p><font face=\"Arial Black\" style=\"line-height: normal;\">B)</font><b style=\"line-height: normal;\"><font face=\"Arial Black\">&nbsp;Linking</font></b></p><p><font face=\"Verdana\"><span style=\"font-size: 0.875rem; line-height: 26.6px;\">Linking has three steps. Verification , Preparation &amp; Resolution.</span><br>&nbsp;&nbsp;<b>Verification</b><br></font>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<font face=\"Verdana\">While implementing the loadClass/findClass Classloader has to call&nbsp;<b><font color=\"#085294\">defineClass</font>&nbsp;</b>function which is the first step of verification. This method is implemented in the Java virtual machine and is responsible for verifying that the class bytes are a legal java class file. Internally, the defineClass method fills out a data Structure that the JVM uses to hold classes. If the class data is malformed, this call will cause a&nbsp;<b>ClassFormatError&nbsp;</b>to be thrown.</font></p><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\"><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp;classByte = byteStream.toByteArray();<br></font><font face=\"Verdana\">&nbsp;<b>result = defineClass(className, classByte, 0, classByte.length, null);</b></font></pre><p><br></p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" style=\"line-height: 26.6px;\"><b>Preparation</b><br></font><span style=\"line-height: 26.6px;\">Preparation involves the creation of static fields of a class or interface and intializing such fields to their default values. This operation may be performed after creation but must complete before Initialization.</span><font face=\"Verdana\"><br></font></p><p><font face=\"Verdana\" style=\"line-height: 26.6px;\"><b>Resolution</b><br></font></p><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\"><span style=\"line-height: 26.6px;\">&nbsp;</span><span class=\"pln\" style=\"font-size: 16px; line-height: 22.4px; white-space: pre-wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">resolveClass</span><span class=\"pun\" style=\"font-size: 16px; line-height: 22.4px; white-space: pre-wrap; color: rgb(102, 102, 0);\">(</span><span class=\"pln\" style=\"font-size: 16px; line-height: 22.4px; white-space: pre-wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">result</span><span class=\"pun\" style=\"font-size: 16px; line-height: 22.4px; white-space: pre-wrap; color: rgb(102, 102, 0);\">);</span><span class=\"pln\" style=\"font-size: 16px; line-height: 22.4px; white-space: pre-wrap; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"> </span></pre><p></p><p><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">The last class loader-specific requirement is to call&nbsp;</span><em style=\"line-height: 25.6px; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 17px;\">resolveClass()</em><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">&nbsp;if the boolean parameter&nbsp;</span><em style=\"line-height: 25.6px; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; font-size: 17px;\">resolveIt</em><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">&nbsp;was true. This method does two things: First, it causes any classes that are referenced by this class explicitly to be loaded and a prototype object for this class to be created; then, it invokes the verifier to do dynamic verification of the legitimacy of the bytecodes in this class. If verification fails, this method call will throw a&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 700; line-height: 25.6px; font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px;\">LinkageError</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">, the most common of which is a&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-weight: 700; line-height: 25.6px; font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px;\">VerifyError</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">.</span></p><p><font face=\"Arial Black\" style=\"line-height: normal;\">C)</font><b style=\"line-height: normal;\"><font face=\"Arial Black\">&nbsp;Intialization</font></b></p><p><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">&nbsp;The last&nbsp;process is to initialize the static fields with the values and call the static blocks. At this stage the Class may be in following four states.</span></p><ol style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px;\"><li><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">This Class object is verified and Prepared but not initialized.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">This Class object is being initialized by some particular thread.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">This Class object is fully intialized and ready for use.</span></li><li><span style=\"font-family: &quot;PT Sans&quot;, &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, sans-serif; color: rgb(22, 22, 29); font-size: 17px; line-height: 25.6px;\">This Class object is in an erroneous state, perhaps because intialization was attempted but failed.</span></li></ol><p>For each class or interface there is a unique lock( Depends on JVM implementation). In each case (except 4 in which it throws NoClassDefFoundError) If it is already being intialized then no further action is taken otherwise either lock is taken or blocked as per the need.&nbsp;</p><p>This is in nutshell explains how a Classloader works in Java.</p><p><br></p><p>READ&nbsp;<a href=\"https://coderszone.in/service/detail?id=2\">How to Create Custom Classloaders ?</a></p><div><br></div><p></p>\n\n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      \n      ','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-13 03:49:17','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-28 13:26:29',0),(2,'How to create a custom classloader in java?','In a JVM, each and every class is loaded by some instance of a java.lang.ClassLoader. The ClassLoader class is located in the java.lang package and developers are free to subclass it to add their own functionality to class loading.Whenever a new JVM is started by typing java MyMainClass, the \"bootstrap class loader\" is responsible for loading key Java classes like java.lang.Object and other runtime code into memory first. The runtime classes are packaged inside of the JRE\\lib\\rt.jar file','<div>In a JVM, each and every class is loaded by some instance of a<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/ClassLoader.html\">&nbsp;java.lang.ClassLoader</a>. The ClassLoader class is located in the&nbsp;<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/package-summary.html\">java.lang package</a>&nbsp;and developers are free to subclass it to add their own functionality to class loading. Whenever a new JVM is started by typing&nbsp;<font color=\"#003163\">java&nbsp;MyMainClass</font>, the \"bootstrap class loader\" is responsible for loading key Java classes like<a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html\">&nbsp;java.lang.Object</a>&nbsp;and other runtime code into memory first. The runtime classes are packaged inside of the JRE\\lib\\rt.jar file. We cannot find the details of the bootstrap class loader in the Java documentation, since this is a native implementation. For the same reason, the behavior of the bootstrap class loader will also differ across JVMs.In a related note, we will get null&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">if we try to get the class loader of a core Java runtime class, like this</span></div><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\">System.out.println(java.lang.String.class.getClassLoader());</pre><div><br></div><div>Next comes the Java extension class loader. We can store extension libraries, those that provide features that go beyond the core Java runtime code, in the path given by the java.ext.dirs property. The ExtClassLoader is responsible for loading all .jar files kept in the java.ext.dirs path. A developer can add his or her own application .jar files or whatever libraries he or she might need to add to the classpath to this extension directory so that they will be loaded by the extension class loader.</div><div><br></div><div>The third and most important class loader from the developer perspective is the AppClassLoader. The application class loader is responsible for loading all of the classes kept in the path corresponding to the java.class.path system property.</div><h3><b>How To create a custom Classloader ?</b></h3><div>Any body can create a custom classloader by extending Classloader and overriding the loadClass Method.&nbsp;</div><div>If you want to read about the working of a classloader first please read &nbsp;how Classloaders work in java ? &nbsp;.</div><div><br></div><div>So lets create a class (say Employee) and package it in a jar file named test.jar. Then we will create a custom classloader to load the class from the jar file. Then we will create a main Class( containing main method) and load the Employee class using our CustomClassloader.</div><div>first lets create a class \"Employee\" and then export it as a jar in eclipse.</div><div><b>Step 1:</b></div><div>Create a new java project \"test\" in eclipse.and in default package create a class name Employee.</div><div><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 1193px;\"><br></div><div><br></div><div>Now export this into a jar file at any location . suppose in \"F:/jar/test.jar\"</div><div><br></div><div><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 1279px;\"><br></div><div><b>Step 2:</b></div><div>create another project and create a class name CustomClassloader.java. and put below code.</div><div><br></div><div><div><br></div><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\">import java.io.ByteArrayOutputStream;<br>import java.io.IOException;<br>import java.io.InputStream;<br>import java.util.Hashtable;<br>import java.util.jar.JarEntry;<br>import java.util.jar.JarFile;<br>public class CustomClassLoader extends ClassLoader {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; private String jarFile = \"F:/jar/test.jar\"; //Path to the jar file<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; private Hashtable classes = new Hashtable(); //used to cache already defined classes<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public CustomClassLoader() {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; super(CustomClassLoader.class.getClassLoader()); //calls the parent class loader\'s constructor<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; @Override<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public Class loadClass(String className, boolean resolveIt) throws ClassNotFoundException {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; return findClass(className, resolveIt);<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; public Class findClass(String className, boolean resolveIt) {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; byte classByte[];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Class result = null;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; result = (Class) classes.get(className); //checks in cached classes<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; if (result != null) {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; return result;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; try {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; return findSystemClass(className); //first try to load this using System Classloaders<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; } catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {<br><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</font>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"> <span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>System.out.println(\"ClassNotFoundException[ \"+className+\" not found by system classloaders]\");<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">		</span>}</font><br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; try {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; JarFile jar = new JarFile(jarFile);<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; JarEntry entry = jar.getJarEntry(className + \".class\");<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; InputStream is = jar.getInputStream(entry);<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ByteArrayOutputStream byteStream = new ByteArrayOutputStream();<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; int nextValue = is.read();<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; while (-1 != nextValue) {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; byteStream.write(nextValue);<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; nextValue = is.read();<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; classByte = byteStream.toByteArray(); //load the class&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; result = defineClass(className, classByte, 0, classByte.length, null); //Create a class instance<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; if (resolveIt) {&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; resolveClass(result); // do the linking&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; classes.put(className, result);<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; return result;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; }catch (IOException e) {<br><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span>System.out.println(\"there is a problem in reading the jar file \"+e.getMessage());<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">		</span>}<br></font>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; return null;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; }<br>}</pre></div><div><br></div><div><b>Step 3:</b></div><div>Create MyMainClass.java file and write following code . to load the class Employee from jar file using our CustomClassloader.</div><div><br></div><div><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\">public class MyMainClass {<br><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span> public static void main(String[] args) {<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">		</span>CustomClassLoader loader=new CustomClassLoader();<br></font><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\"><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">		<br></font></span><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">			</span>Class emp = null;<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">			</span>try {<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">				</span>emp = loader.loadClass(\"Employee\",true);<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">			</span>} catch (ClassNotFoundException e) {<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">				</span>System.out.println(\"Class Not found \"+e.getMessage());<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">			</span>}<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">			</span>System.out.println(\"Name of the class loaded = \" + emp.getName());<br></font><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\"><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">		<br></font></span><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\">	</span> }<br></font>}</pre></div><div><br></div><div>If you run the above code and you get error something like this&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: Consolas, Monaco, &quot;Andale Mono&quot;, &quot;Ubuntu Mono&quot;, monospace; font-size: inherit; line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; background-color: transparent;\">Exception </span><span class=\"token keyword\" style=\"font-size: inherit; line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; color: rgb(0, 119, 170); background-color: transparent;\">in</span><span style=\"font-family: Consolas, Monaco, &quot;Andale Mono&quot;, &quot;Ubuntu Mono&quot;, monospace; font-size: inherit; line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; background-color: transparent;\"> thread </span><span class=\"token string\" style=\"font-size: inherit; line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; color: rgb(102, 153, 0); background-color: transparent;\">\"main\"</span><span style=\"font-family: Consolas, Monaco, &quot;Andale Mono&quot;, &quot;Ubuntu Mono&quot;, monospace; font-size: inherit; line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre; word-spacing: normal; background-color: transparent;\"> java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError: </span></div><div>It means there is difference in the java version in generating the jar ie test project and the main project. So go to window -&gt;preferences -&gt; java and verify that for both project same java version is being used in eclipse.</div><div><br></div><div>Okay ! so if you do not get the above error its pretty fine.</div><div>you should get below output .</div><div><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\">ClassNotFoundException[ Employee not found by system classloaders]<br>Name of the class loaded = Employee</pre></div><div><br></div><div><b>Explanation of the Code:</b></div><div>To create a custom Classloader we have to extend Classloader and override its loadClass method. So we have followed the simple principle of Classloading.</div><div>ie. First try to load by using the parent classloaders and if ClassNotFound then try to load by our custom classloader by reading the byte codes of .class file. Next is to&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">call the defineClass which verifies the bytecodes and defines the classes in JVM. The last call is to resolveClass which is for linking/resolution of the classes.</span></div><div><br></div><div><b>What happens if we remove the below code from findClass method ?</b></div><div><pre style=\"line-height: 1.42857;\"> return findSystemClass(className);</pre></div><div><br></div><div>Ans: In this case ClassLoading Delegation Heirarchy is broken. So when there is a request to defineClass it will try to Access java.lang.Object which cannot be loaded by this Classloader and it wont be available . Hence it will throw NoClassDefFoundError.</div><div><br></div>\n\n      ','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-22 06:08:25','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-22 06:08:25',0),(3,'JVM architecture explained.','Java virtual machine is explained with clearity. What is a virtual machine ? What is the function of JVM? Types of JVM . What are the different components of jvm ? What is a classloader Subsystem ? What Are different memory Area and why it is used? All these questions can be answered after reading this article.','\n          \n          \n          \n          <h3>JVM Architecture overview.</h3><div><br></div><div><b>What is a virtual machine ?</b></div><div><br></div><div>A virtual machine is a software implementation of a machine (ie a computer) that executes programs like a physical machine.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Java Virtual Machine</b></div><div>Java main benefit is Write once Run anywhere. This functionality is achieved by using JVM. JVM is a virtual machine that runs java bytecode by creating five identical runtime areas.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">The java compiler compiles the </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&lt;ClassName&gt;.java</b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"> file and generates a bytecode file </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5;\">&lt;className&gt;.class</b><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"> which is a JVM understandable format.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">JVM loads the bytecode and keeps in memory area, Where runtime engine executes the instructions and read/write from/to the memory area. </span></div><div><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><br></span></div><div><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><font color=\"#295218\"><b>We would learn it in detail.</b></font></span></div><div><br></div><div><b>What is a class file and what information it stores in byte code format ?</b></div><div><b><br></b></div><div>You can deassemble a java.class file to see the bytecode information.&nbsp;<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">Suppose we have a class file Employee.class generated from Employee.java.</span></div><pre>//Employee.java<br>public class Employee {<br><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>public static void print(){<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">		</span>System.out.println(\"Hello !this is print from Employee\");<br></font><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>}<br></font>}</pre><div><br></div><div>Now if you run command to deassemble the Employee.class file you will find following contents in the bytecode.</div><pre>javap -c Employee ( For a detailed information you may try javap -v Employee)<br>Compiled from \"Employee.java\"<br>public class Employee {<br>&nbsp; public Employee();<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Code:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;0: aload_0<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;1: invokespecial #8 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;// Method java/lang/Object.\"&lt;init&gt;\":()V<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4: return<br>&nbsp; public static void print();<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; Code:<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;0: getstatic &nbsp; &nbsp; #15 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Field java/lang/System.out:Ljava/io/PrintStream;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3: ldc &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; #21 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // String Hello !this is print from Employee<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;5: invokevirtual #23 &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; // Method java/io/PrintStream.println:(Ljava/lang/String;)V<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;8: return<br>}</pre><div><br></div><div>So a java .Class file has various information regarding Class/interface.<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">The outline of a Java class file is as follows:&nbsp;</span></div><div><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\"><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">	</font></span></div><pre>ClassFile {<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u4 magic;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 minor_version;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 major_version;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 constant_pool_count;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; cp_info constant_pool[constant_pool_count-1];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 access_flags;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 this_class;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 super_class;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 interfaces_count;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 interfaces[interfaces_count];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 fields_count;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; field_info fields[fields_count];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 methods_count;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; method_info methods[methods_count];<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; u2 attributes_count;<br>&nbsp; &nbsp; attribute_info attributes[attributes_count];<br><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span>}</font></pre><div><br></div><div>The above is included in \"4.1. The ClassFile Structure\" of \"The Java Virtual Machine Specification, Second Edition\".</div><div><br></div><div>The first 16 bytes of the Employee.class file disassembled earlier are shown as follows in the Hex Editor ( If you have notepad++ it has a plugin for Hex editor).</div><div><br></div><div><b>CAFEBABE20202033201F072002012008</b></div><div><br></div><div><b>With this value, see the class file format.</b></div><div><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\"><b>magic: </b>The first 4 bytes of the class file are the magic number. This is a pre-specified value to distinguish the Java class file. As shown in the Hex Editor above, the value is always 0xCAFEBABE. In short, when the first 4 bytes of a file is 0xCAFEBABE, it can be regarded as the Java class file. This is a kind of \"witty\" magic number related to the name \"Java\".</span><br></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;</div><div><b> minor_version, major_version:</b> The next 4 bytes indicate the class version. As the Employee.class file is 0x20202033, the class version is 51.0. The version of a class file compiled by JDK 1.7 is 51.0, and the version of a class file compiled by JDK 1.6 is 50.0. The JVM must maintain backward compatibility with class files compiled in a lower version than itself. On the other hand, when a upper-version class file is executed in the lower-version JVM, java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError occurs.</div><div><br></div><div><b>constant_pool_count, constant_pool[]:</b> Next to the version, the class-type constant pool information is described. This is the information included in the Runtime Constant Pool area, which will be explained later. While loading the class file, the JVM includes the constant_pool information in the Runtime Constant Pool area of the method area. As the constant_pool_count of the Employee.class file is 0x201F, you can see that the constant_pool has (8223-1) indexes, 8222 indexes.</div><div><br></div><div><b>access_flags: </b>This is the flag that shows the modifier information of a class; in other words, it shows public, final, abstract or whether or not to interface.</div><div><br></div><div><b>this_class, super_class: </b>The index in the constant_pool for the class corresponding to this and super, respectively.</div><div><b>interfaces_count, interfaces[]: </b>The index in the the constant_pool for the number of interfaces implemented by the class and each interface.</div><div><b>fields_count, fields[]:</b> The number of fields and the field information of the class. The field information includes the field name, type information, modifier, and index in the constant_pool.</div><div><b>methods_count, methods[]:</b> The number of methods in a class and the methods information of the class. The methods information includes the methods name, type and number of the parameters, return type, modifier, index in the constant_pool, execution code of the method, and exception information.</div><div><b>attributes_count, attributes[]:</b> The attribute_info structure has various attributes. For field_info or method_info, attribute_info is used.</div><div><br></div><div><font color=\"#295218\"><b>So this is what inside a class file !</b></font></div><div><br></div><div><b><font color=\"#0000ff\">Do you know there is a 65535 byte limit of method size in java ? Do you Know why ?</font></b> <a href=\"https://coderszone.in/service/detail?id=4\">Read Why there is a 65535 byte limit of method size in java</a>.</div><div><br></div><div><b>Now jvm has following architecture and components.</b></div><div style=\"text-align: center; \"><img src=\"https://coderszone.in/service/upfile/get/1466840727682/png\" style=\"width: 747px;\"><br></div><div><b>1) Classloader subsystem.</b></div><div>&nbsp;Class loader Subsystem has task of loading the Bytecode of .class files into Memory area, Verifying the bytecode,linking &amp; intialization.<span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">&nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"https://coderszone.in/service/detail?id=1\">Read How classloaders work in detail here</a>.</span></div><div><b>2) Memory Area</b></div><div><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">Runtime memory Areas are the memory areas assigned when the JVM program runs on the OS. The runtime memory areas can be divided into 6 areas.&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">Of the six, one PC Register, JVM Stack, and Native Method Stack are created for one thread.</span><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"line-height: 1.5; white-space: pre;\">	</span><span style=\"font-family: &quot;Helvetica Neue&quot;, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif; line-height: 1.5;\">Heap, Method Area, and Runtime Constant Pool are shared by all threads.</span></div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <b>a) PC register:</b> One PC (Program Counter) register exists for one thread, and is created when the thread starts. PC register has the address of a JVM instruction being executed now.</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <b>b) JVM stack:</b> One JVM stack exists for one thread, and is created when the thread starts. It is a stack that saves the struct (Stack Frame). The JVM just pushes or pops the stack frame to the JVM stack. If any exception occurs, each line of the stack trace shown as a method such as printStackTrace() expresses one stack frame.</div><div><br></div><div style=\"text-align: center; \"><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\">	</span></font><img src=\"https://coderszone.in/service/upfile/get/1467120697888/png\" style=\"width: 711px;\"></div><div><span class=\"Apple-tab-span\" style=\"white-space:pre\"><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\">	</font></span></div><div><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><b>Stack frame:</b> One stack frame is created whenever a method is executed in the JVM, and the stack frame is added to the JVM stack of the thread. When the method is ended, the stack frame is removed. Each stack frame has the reference for local variable array, Operand stack, and runtime constant pool of a class where the method being executed belongs. The size of local variable array and Operand stack is determined while compiling. Therefore, the size of stack frame is fixed according to the method.</font></div><div><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><b>Local variable array:</b> It has an index starting from 0. 0 is the reference of a class instance where the method belongs. From 1, the parameters sent to the method are saved. After the method parameters, the local variables of the method are saved.</font></div><div><font face=\"Helvetica Neue, Helvetica, Roboto, Arial, sans-serif\"><b>Operand stack:</b> An actual workspace of a method. Each method exchanges data between the Operand stack and the local variable array, and pushes or pops other method invoke results. The necessary size of the Operand stack space can be determined during compiling. Therefore, the size of the Operand stack can also be determined during compiling.</font></div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <b>c) Native method stack:</b> A stack for native code written in a language other than Java. In other words, it is a stack used to execute C/C++ codes invoked through JNI (Java Native Interface). According to the language, a C stack or C++ stack is created.</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp;<b> d) Method area:</b> The method area is shared by all threads, created when the JVM starts. It stores runtime constant pool, field and method information, static variable, and method bytecode for each of the classes and interfaces read by the JVM. The method area can be implemented in various formats by JVM vendor. Oracle Hotspot JVM calls it Permanent Area or Permanent Generation (PermGen). The garbage collection for the method area is optional for each JVM vendor.</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <b>e) Runtime constant pool:</b> An area that corresponds to the constant_pool table in the class file format. This area is included in the method area; however, it plays the most core role in JVM operation. Therefore, the JVM specification separately describes its importance. As well as the constant of each class and interface, it contains all references for methods and fields. In short, when a method or field is referred to, the JVM searches the actual address of the method or field on the memory by using the runtime constant pool.</div><div>&nbsp; &nbsp; <b>f) Heap:</b> A space that stores instances or objects, and is a target of garbage collection. This space is most frequently mentioned when discussing issues such as JVM performance. JVM vendors can determine how to configure the heap or not to collect garbage.</div><div><br></div><div><b>3) Runtime Engine</b></div><div>The bytecode that is assigned to the runtime data areas in the JVM via class loader is executed by the Runtime execution engine. The execution engine reads the Java Bytecode in the unit of instruction. It is like a CPU executing the machine command one by one. Each command of the bytecode consists of a 1-byte OpCode and additional Operand. The execution engine gets one OpCode and execute task with the Operand, and then executes the next OpCode.</div><div><a href=\"#\">Read How runtime engine works in JVM in detail.</a></div><div><br></div><div><b>4) Garbage Collector.</b></div><div>Garbage collector Main task is to free the heap memory from unused objects. <a href=\"#\">Read in detail about Garbage Collector in java</a>&nbsp;</div><div><b>5) Java Native interface</b></div><div>Some of the functionalities are specific to the native platform . JVM has a native interface which can call the native functions from the Java Native library.</div><div><br></div>\n\n      \n      \n      \n      \n      ','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-22 11:19:21','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-28 13:57:58',0),(4,'Why there is a 65535 byte limit of method size in java ?','The JVM has a limitation that the size of one method can not be more than 65535 bytes. Sometimes while writing and executing jsp on tomcat you may get an wrror like \"Servlet.service() for servlet jsp threw exception org.apache.jasper.JasperException: Unable to compile class for JSP Generated servlet error:\nThe code of method _jspService(HttpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse) is exceeding the 65535 bytes limit\". The reason is method size limit on JVM.','When writing and executing jsp sometimes you may encounter a situation like below<br><br><pre>Servlet.service() for servlet jsp threw exception org.apache.jasper.JasperException: Unable to compile class for JSP Generated servlet error:<br>The code of method _jspService(HttpServletRequest, HttpServletResponse) is exceeding the 65535 bytes limit\"</pre><br>The above error may vary according to Web Application Server. However This issue reason is because there is a limitation of jvm that a method can only have maximum of 65535 byte. So why is this size limit in jvm?<br><br>The branching/jump instructions in java byte code are \"goto\" and \"jsr\" &amp; both recieve operands of 2 bytes of space that reflects offset as signed index. As two bytes in signed way can have 65535 index as maximum, Jvm Supports only 65535 bytes for a method declaration.<br><br><pre>goto [branchbyte1] [branchbyte2]<br>jsr [branchbyte1] [branchbyte2]</pre><br><div>However, to support more sufficient branch, Java Bytecode prepares \"goto_w\" and \"jsr_w\" that receive 4-byte signed branch offset.</div><pre>goto_w [branchbyte1] [branchbyte2] [branchbyte3] [branchbyte4]<br>jsr_w [branchbyte1] [branchbyte2] [branchbyte3] [branchbyte4]</pre><div>With the two, branch is available with an index exceeding 65535. Therefore, the 65535 byte limit of Java method may be overcome. However, due to various other limits of the Java class file format, the Java method still cannot exceed 65535 bytes.</div><div><br></div>','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-23 10:37:06','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-23 10:37:06',0),(5,'How a runtime engine works in java ?','The bytecode that is assigned to the runtime areas in the jvm via classloader is executed by the runtime engine line by line. The Runtime Execution Engine reads the instructions \nfrom the java bytecode and execute it one by one. Its just like a CPU executing machine command one by one. Each command of the bytecode consists of a 1-byte OpCode and additional Operand. The execution engine gets one OpCode and execute task with the Operand, and then executes the next OpCode.','<p>Read in detail <a href=\"https://coderszone.in/service/detail?id=3\">JVM Explained</a> before this topic<br></p><p>The\n bytecode that is assigned to the runtime areas in the jvm via \nclassloader is executed by the runtime engine line by line. The Runtime \nExecution Engine reads the instructions <br>from the java bytecode and \nexecute it one by one. Its just like a CPU executing machine command one\n by one. Each command of the bytecode consists of a 1-byte OpCode and \nadditional Operand. The execution engine gets one OpCode and execute \ntask with the Operand, and then executes the next OpCode.<br>But the \nJava Bytecode is written in a language that a human can understand, \nrather than in the language that the machine directly executes. \nTherefore, the execution engine must change the bytecode to the language\n that can be executed by the machine in the JVM. The bytecode can be \nchanged to the suitable language in one of two ways.</p><p><br><b>Interpreter:</b>\n Reads, interprets and executes the bytecode instructions one by one. As\n it interprets and executes instructions one by one, it can quickly \ninterpret one bytecode, but slowly executes the interpreted result. This\n is the disadvantage of the interpret language. The \'language\' called \nBytecode basically runs like an interpreter.<br><br><b>JIT (Just-In-Time) compiler:</b>\n The JIT compiler has been introduced to compensate for the \ndisadvantages of the interpreter. The execution engine runs as an \ninterpreter first, and at the appropriate time, the JIT compiler \ncompiles the entire bytecode to change it to native code. After that, \nthe execution engine no longer interprets the method, but directly \nexecutes using native code. Execution in native code is much faster than\n interpreting instructions one by one. The compiled code can be executed\n quickly since the native code is stored in the cache. <br><br>However, \nit takes more time for JIT compiler to compile the code than for the \ninterpreter to interpret the code one by one. Therefore, if the code is \nto be executed just once, it is better to interpret it instead of \ncompiling. Therefore, the JVMs that use the JIT compiler internally \ncheck how frequently the method is executed and compile the method only \nwhen the frequency is higher than a certain level.<br></p><div align=\"center\"><img data-filename=\"clipboard.png\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 859px;\"><br></div><p><br>JVM\n has no specification on Runtime execution engine so Different JVM \nvendors improve their execution engines using various techniques and \nhence there are different types of JIT compilers.<br><br></p><blockquote>Note\n : The technique in which an Intermediate language like Bytecode is \nintroduced, there is virtual machine that execute that code and JIT \ncompilers improves the performance of the JVM.This technique is commonly\n used in other languages based on Virtual Machine that have intermediate\n language in common line Microsoft .Net, CLR(Common language runtime) \netc.<br></blockquote><p></p><p><br>Most JIT compilers run as shown in the figure below.<br></p><div align=\"center\"><img data-filename=\"clipboard.png\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" style=\"width: 694px;\"><br></div><p><br>The\n traditional compilers compile all the code before the program is first \nrun, however JIT( Just in Time) compilers runs after the program has \nstarted and compiles the bytecode on the fly.Oracle Hotspot JVM uses JIT\n compiler. The name Hotspot comes from the way it compiles and run the \ncode. In practical there is always a small subset of code is run very \nfrequently so using interpreter to run the code is not so good for \noptimization. So its always better to compile that subset of code in \nnative form which will reduce the execution time significantly and hence\n comes JIT( just in time compiler) which finds the hotspots( frequently \nrunning piece of codes) and compiles them in the native code to improve \nthe run time performance. The Hotspot Compiler(JIT) also removes the \nnative code compiled and kept in cache if \"it is no longer frequently \ninvoked\" and runs in interpreter mode.<br></p><p><br><b>The hotspot VM is also of two types</b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) Hotspot Client VM.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; 2) Hotspot Server VM.<br><br>Both\n use identical runtime however Hotspot server uses an advanced dynamic \noptimizing compiler which is more complex and it uses more diverse \nperformance optimization techniques. IBM JVM has introduced AOT(Ahead of\n time) compiler from IBM JDK 1.6 as well as the JIT compiler.In short a \ncode already compiled through the AOT compiler can be used by another \nJVM without compiling. IBM jvm also provides a fast way of execution by \ngenerating a precompiled code JXE format using the AOT compiler.</p>\n\n      ','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-27 11:29:11','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-27 11:29:11',0),(6,'Singleton Design pattern','There are various ways of creating a singleton pattern and its pros and cons.\nThe minimum things that are required for creating a Singleton Class is as below.\n              1) make the constructor private so that its constructor cannot be called from outside the class.\n              2) Use a public static variable to hold the instance.\n               3) create a public static Instance getter method. and in that method if instance is null create the instance for the first time .','<h5>What is a singleton design pattern ?</h5><blockquote>A singleton \ndesign pattern is creational design pattern in which we ensure that \nthere is only single instance of a class can be created and used.<br></blockquote><p>There are various ways of creating a singleton pattern and its pros and cons.<br>The minimum things that are required for creating a Singleton Class is as below.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 1) make the constructor private so that its constructor cannot be called from outside the class.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 2) Use a public static variable to hold the instance.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\n 3) create a public static Instance getter method. and in that method if\n instance is null create the instance for the first time .<br><br>The code can be as below.<br></p><pre>public class MySingleton{<br><br>   private static MySingleton instance;<br>   private MySingleton() {<br>     super();<br>   }<br>   public static MySingleton getInstance() {<br>      if (instance == null) {<br>      instance = new MySingleton();<br>      }<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;return instance;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>    }<br>}</pre><p><br>However the above code has multiple loopholes . The above is not thread safe and can be broken using several other methods.<br><font color=\"#003163\">Lets see how.</font><br><br>If we run the below code it will generate two different hashcodes stating that we are able to create two different instances of this singleton. Which should not be the case. It Means the code is not thread safe.<br></p><pre>public class MyMainClass extends Thread {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;public static void main(String[] args) {<br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Thread t1 = new MyMainClass();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Thread t2 = new MyMainClass();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; t1.start();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  t2.start();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>    @Override<br>    public void run() {&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>        MySingleton single = MySingleton.getInstance();<br>        System.out.println(single.hashCode());<br>    }<br>}</pre><pre>Output:<br>1137582276<br>1011870493</pre><p><br></p><h5>Early Intialization:</h5><p>So the above code is not thread safe and we can achieve it by using early initialization. In this way we initialize the Singleton Class at the time of loading the class and use the same instance on-wards.<br>Like below:<br></p><pre>public class MySingleton{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;private static MySingleton instance=new MySingleton();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public static MySingleton getInstance() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;return instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}</pre><p><br>This way the thread safety problem is resolved however it is inefficient because the instance is initialized at Classloading and not when it is required.<br><br></p><h5>Synchronized instantiation:</h5><p>So its better to use a synchronized block With double null checking to instantiate the class. In this way the Instance would be created only when required and will also be thread safe.<br></p><pre>public class MySingleton {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;private static MySingleton instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;private MySingleton() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;super();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;public static MySingleton getInstance() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if (instance == null) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;synchronized (MySingleton.class) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if (instance == null) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;instance = new MySingleton();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;return instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}</pre><p>So when we run the <font color=\"#085294\">MyMainClass.java</font> it gives output as below. It means we have resolved the thread safety issue.<br></p><pre>2000218524<br>2000218524</pre><p><br></p><h5>Handle Serialization / De-serialization:</h5><p>The above code would be broken again if you serialize and again de-serialize the Instance object.<br>For example if you run this code below it will generate different Hashcode ( Remember to add Serializable Interface to The MySingleton Class).<br><br></p><pre>import java.io.FileInputStream;<br>import java.io.FileOutputStream;<br>import java.io.IOException;<br>import java.io.ObjectInputStream;<br>import java.io.ObjectOutputStream;<br>public class MyMainClass{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException, ClassNotFoundException {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MySingleton s1=MySingleton.getInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;System.out.println(s1.hashCode());<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;FileOutputStream fs= new FileOutputStream(\"c:\\\\obj.ser\");<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ObjectOutputStream ob=new ObjectOutputStream(fs);<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ob.writeObject(s1);<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ob.close();&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;// Read<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;FileInputStream fin=new FileInputStream(\"c:\\\\obj.ser\");<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ObjectInputStream obin=new ObjectInputStream(fin);<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MySingleton s2=(MySingleton) obin.readObject();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;obin.close();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;System.out.println(s2.hashCode());<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}<br>Output:<br>366712642<br>245257410</pre><p>So again using serialization when this code is broken . so to Protect from serialization we would have to add readResolve method to The Singleton Class.<br><br></p><pre>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;protected Object readResolve() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; return getInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}</pre><p>Now by adding this method to MySingleton now output is like below<br>output:<br></p><pre>366712642<br>366712642</pre><p><br></p><h5>Handle reflection:</h5><p><br>But there is another way we can break this by using reflection. Using reflection we can get hold of the constructors and then be changing its access we can invoke it.<br>Which will again break our Singleton pattern.<br><br></p><pre>import java.lang.reflect.Constructor;<br>import java.lang.reflect.InvocationTargetException;<br>public class MyMainClass{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;public static void main(String[] args) throws InstantiationException, IllegalAccessException, IllegalArgumentException, InvocationTargetException {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MySingleton s1=MySingleton.getInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;System.out.println(s1.hashCode());<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MySingleton s2=null;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Constructor[] constructors= MySingleton.class.getDeclaredConstructors();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;for(Constructor constructor:constructors){<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;constructor.setAccessible(true);<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;s2=(MySingleton) constructor.newInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;break;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;System.out.println(s2!=null?s2.hashCode():null);<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}<br>Output:<br>366712642<br>1829164700</pre><p><br>So in order to protect it from being broken by reflection we can check if instance is already created in private constructor and prevent it from creating if it is true.<br><br>for example:<br></p><pre>import java.io.Serializable;<br>public class MySingleton implements Serializable{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;private static MySingleton instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;private MySingleton() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if(instance != null){<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;throw new RuntimeException(\"Sorry this cannot be initialized by any other way please call getInstance method.\");<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;public static MySingleton getInstance() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if (instance == null) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;synchronized (MySingleton.class) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if (instance == null) {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;instance = new MySingleton();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;return instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;protected Object readResolve() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; return getInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}</pre><p><br></p><h3><font color=\"#295218\"><b>Now this above code is quite safe to be used as a singleton pattern.</b></font></h3><p>There are various other ways also to create a singleton Class.<br></p><h5>1) Bill Pugh Singleton Implementation</h5><p>Prior to java 5 there were various issues with above approach and in the scenario when several threads try to get Instance simultaneously the above approach failed sometimes. So Bill Pugh came up with a different approach to create Singleton class using a inner static helper class. The Bill Pugh Singleton implementation goes like this.<br></p><pre>&nbsp; import java.io.Serializable;<br>&nbsp; public class MySingleton implements Serializable{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; private static class SingletonHelper{<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; private static MySingleton instance = new MySingleton();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;private MySingleton() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;if(SingletonHelper.instance != null){<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;throw new RuntimeException(\"Sorry this cannot be initialized by any other way please call getInstance method.\");<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;public static MySingleton getInstance() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;return SingletonHelper.instance;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;protected Object readResolve() {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; return getInstance();<br>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;}<br>}</pre><p><br></p><h5>2) Another way is to create a singleton using Enum.</h5><p>Joshua Bloch suggests the use of Enum to implement Singleton design pattern as Java ensures that any enum value is instantiated only once in a Java program. Since Java Enum values are globally accessible, so is the singleton. The drawback is that the enum type is somewhat inflexible; for example, it does not allow lazy initialization.<br><br></p><pre>public enum EnumSingleton {<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; INSTANCE;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; public static void doSomething(){<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; //do something<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; }<br>}</pre><p><br><br></p>\n\n      ','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-28 10:23:28','vivek.tiwarics@gmail.com','2016-06-28 10:23:28',0);
